<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   Turkey Takes a Big Risk, for the West
</HL>
<DATE>
09/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A15
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP MDEST
</CO>
<LP>
   Your Aug. 10 editorial "The Forgotten Ally" was a welcome
recognition of Turkey's unflinching defense of Western
interests. Turkey has been a staunch ally since the formation
of the Turkish republic following World War I. Shutting off
the Iraqi pipeline without even a blink and immediately
beginning the embargo against Iraq is yet another example of
Turkey's devotion to Western ideals.
   That the path taken by Turkey is an extremely costly one
both for the short term and for the long haul is
unquestioned. A casual look at the map reveals that Turkey
has enjoyed a trusting relationship with Iraq. Why would Iraq
build a pipeline that goes north for miles to enter Turkey
before heading west to reach the Mediterranean when a much
shorter route was available directly west through Syria? The
Iraqis trusted their lifeline to the dependable Turks in
preference to their fellow Arabs, the Syrians. Aside from the
immediate loss of $2 billion to $3 billion a year in business
with Iraq and $3 billion in back payments, Turkey faces an
uncertain future with its erstwhile trusting neighbor.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Following your laudatory editorial, you became the target
(not unexpectedly) of anti-Turkish voices emanating from
individuals with Greek surnames (Letters, Aug. 30). Turkey's
alliance with the West is anathema to these folks who are
still fighting World War I against the Ottoman Empire. Every
time somebody says something nice about Turkey, they come out
slinging mud, with misstated facts, exaggerated half-truths
and absolute lies.
   For the record, Turkey did not invade Cyprus. Turkey
fulfilled its lawful obligation, as Greece and Britain could
also have done, to protect the integrity of Cyprus, which had
fallen into the hands of the military junta then ruling
Greece. Ironically, the Turkish action benefited Greece
immensely by giving the junta a bloody nose and opening the
way for democracy to return to its birthplace in Athens.
   For the record, torture is not condoned in Turkey. It is
against the law. What we call police brutality, illegally
practiced by certain overzealous officers in the U.S.,
becomes government-sanctioned torture in Turkey as related by
those who are still fighting World War I.
   For the record, there were no pogroms in Turkey to
diminish the minority populations. Any non-Turkish citizen of
Turkey who left Turkey left for the same reason we Turks left
-- to seek better economic opportunities abroad.
   Ali F. Sevin
   President
   Assembly of Turkish American Associations
   Washington
   ---
   Your editorial stated, "The Senate passes resolutions
wallowing in the Armenian tragedies of the old Ottoman
Empire. . . ." I resent the use of the term, "wallowing" and
wonder whether my Jewish friends have been wallowing also in
the tragedies of the Holocaust.
   Any infection, left untreated, continues to be destructive
to the body. Any conflict, left unresolved, continues to
erupt in strife. Any tragedy, left unrecognized, continues to
haunt future generations. Oedipus or the Old Testament
stories of David and Absalom (to name a few literary sources)
are but a reminder of such truths.
   Pauline Melikian House
   Somerset, Ky.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900920-0093
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900920-0093.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   National Steel Sets
   Venture With NKK
   And Dofasco Inc.
   ----
   By Clare Ansberry
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6
</SO>
<CO>
   J.NKK T.DFS NII
</CO>
<IN>
STEEL MANUFACTURERS (STL)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   PITTSBURGH -- National Steel Corp., NKK Corp. of Japan and
Dofasco Inc. of Canada agreed to build a $200 million steel
galvanizing line, in what is believed to be the first
steel-related venture involving three countries.
   The multination project could launch a new round of joint
agreements in the U.S., where such relationships have
consisted mainly of Japanese-American partnerships. "This is
a model for global cooperation and in that sense is an
extremely important milestone," said John Jacobson, an
analyst with AUS Consultants.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   He noted that such ventures should help steelmakers'
viability by reducing the potential for excess capacity,
which has been the industry's nemesis. "There are too many
players for each company to do its own thing," he said.
   The plant, scheduled for completion by early 1993, will
produce about 400,000 tons of hot-dip coated steel annually
for the automotive market. Although a site hasn't been
selected for this venture, the plant will likely be built
along the U.S.-Canadian border, close to auto makers in
Detroit. The site must also be close to National Steel and
Dofasco plants, each of which will supply 50% of the raw
steel.
   High-quality, corrosion resistant coated steel has been
the industry's darling in recent years, with steelmakers
rushing to add lines. The electrogalvanizing coating process
has been considered superior to hot-dip because the first
process covers steel more uniformly, which is essential for
exposed car panels. However, the hot-dip process has improved
in terms of consistency and is making a comeback because it's
cheaper and more flexible.
   The flurry to build coating lines could create a glut in
the next few years. John Lichtenstein, a director at Beddows
Co., an international consulting firm, believes demand for
coated steel will grow for both automotive and construction
markets. Whether supply exceeds demand, he said, depends
largely on the ability of Japanese auto transplants to expand
the U.S. car market, as opposed to supplanting U.S. auto
makers.
   NKK will supply equipment and provide technical and
operational assistance, patterning the plant after one of its
Japanese facilities. Dofasco and National Steel will each
market and distribute one-half of the total output to their
existing automotive customers.
   Dofasco will own 50% of the venture, NKK 40%, and National
Steel, which is 70%-owned by NKK, will own the remaining 10%.
Ben J. Ciprietti, vice president, planning of Dofasco, will
be president, while a NKK director and two National Steel
executives will be directors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900920-0092
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900920-0092.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   Unattractive Genius
   Made Beautiful Science
</HL>
<DATE>
09/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A15
</SO>
<LP>
   In his book review of "A Literary Guide to Science"
(Leisure &amp; Arts, Aug. 17), Jim Holt writes: "A particularly
unattractive physicist named Otto Warburg accepts the status
of `honorary Aryan' from the Nazis so that he can remain in
his Berlin laboratory even though he is half Jewish."
   The Otto Warburg to whom Mr. Holt refers was of course not
a physicist but a biochemist, indeed the most notable
biochemist of his time, perhaps of any time. The body of work
for which he received a Nobel Prize includes his famous
determination of the action spectrum of the "respiratory
enzyme." This was not only a technical tour de force but also
on the purely aesthetic level one of the most beautiful
experiments of the 20th century.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Warburg is the subject of a brief, highly readable
biography "Otto Warburg: Cell Physiologist, Biochemist and
Eccentric" (Oxford University Press, 1981) by Sir Hans Krebs.
Sir Hans, himself a Nobel Prize-winning biochemist, was a
Jewish scientist forced to flee to England from the Nazi
butchers. He knew Warburg as well as anyone could claim to
know him, having worked for some years in Warburg's
institute. His criticism of certain aspects of Warburg's
personality and career is unsparing but he is also generous
in his admiration of Warburg's genius and his devotion to
science.
   Eugene P. Kennedy
   Professor of Biological Chemistry
   Harvard Medical School
   Boston
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900920-0091
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900920-0091.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Court Allows Officials
   To Pursue Nevada Site
   For Nuclear Dumping
</HL>
<DATE>
09/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<IN>
ENVIRONMENT (ENV)
NUCLEAR POWER, FUEL (NUK)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
ENERGY DEPARTMENT (ERG)
</GV>
<LP>
   SAN FRANCISCO -- The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
ruled Wednesday that federal energy officials may pursue
Nevada as a potential nuclear waste dump site, despite the
state Legislature's adamant opposition.
   The uananimous court decision allows government officials
to proceed with a massive environmental study of Nevada's
Yucca Mountain, about one hundreds miles northeast of Las
Vegas, as a burial site for radioactive wastes. The state has
mounted several legal challenges to the federal plan since
1987, and the state Legislature has passed hostile
resolutions and refused to supply the government with
necessary environmental permits.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The three-judge panel rejected state arguments that the
federal government was violating constitutional protections
of state rights, as well as provisions of the U.S. Nuclear
Waste Policy Act. The state attorney general had argued in
August before the court that Congress failed to override
Nevada's disapproval notice within the 90 days required under
the 1982 act.
   In his decision, federal Judge Arthur Alarcon asserted
that the U.S. energy secretary was correct in arguing that
the U.S. Constitutions's 10th amendment "does not protect a
state from being outvoted in Congress."
   Originally the federal government was considering five
sites in Mississippi, Utah, Texas, Washington and Nevada.
Since 1987, the government has narrowed the list to three --
in Hannaford, Wash., Deafsmith, Texas, and Yucca Mountain --
and more recently dropped all but the Nevada location.
   Nevada can appeal the decision to the U.S. Supreme Court
or ask the appellate court for reconsideration. State Deputy
Attorney General Harry Swainston wouldn't say whether the
state will appeal until he reads the decision. But in August,
state Attorney General Brian McKay vowed "to use every tool
possible" to keep the dump site out of the state.
   The federal energy officials have said that its "site
verification study" would take about six to ten years to
complete. So far, government researchers have bored several
exploratory holes in the mountainside, but their work largely
halted in the face of state resistance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900920-0090
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900920-0090.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   Ohio Industry Reborn?
   Better Look Again
</HL>
<DATE>
09/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A15
</SO>
<LP>
   In your Aug. 17 page-one article "Comeback Story: Reborn
Ohio Industry Is Clean, High-Tech and Shock-Absorbent," the
idea that "Manufacturing has come roaring back" seems overly
optimistic, when one checks the official figures. According
to the Bureau of Economic Analysis of the U.S. Commerce
Department, in 1969 Ohio ranked 15th among the states in
per-capita personal income. By 1988 -- the latest year for
which comparable figures are available -- Ohio's rank was
down to 24th. The bureau projected a further drop to 25 by
the year 2000.
   Over a period of decades Ohio has been gaining in low-wage
and part-time jobs, while losing many thousands of high-wage,
full-time jobs. In 1969, for example, employment in
manufacturing industries in Ohio averaged 1,471,000. By 1989
that level had dropped to 1,123,000 -- a loss of 348,000
jobs.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Production workers in Ohio manufacturing industries
averaged $523 a week in 1989. Had the 1969 level of factory
employment been achieved in 1989, personal income of Ohioans
would have been greater by at least $10 billion.
   William Papier
   Columbus, Ohio
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900920-0089
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900920-0089.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Trump Again
   Seeks to Delay
   Loan Payment
   ---
   Payout for Airline Shuttle
   Is Due in Three Weeks;
   Bailout Pact Seems Safe
   ----
   By Neil Barsky
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   X.TMP CCI
</CO>
<IN>
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
AIRLINES (AIR)
MAJOR MONEY CENTER BANKS (BAN)
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<LP>
   Less than a month after concluding a $65 million bank
bailout, Donald J. Trump returned to his bankers to seek a
delay in loan payments due on the Trump Shuttle airline.
   Mr. Trump and two aides met yesterday with officials from
Citibank, a unit of Citicorp, which issued the shuttle loan,
to ask the bank to restructure $245 million in debt payments
still due, saying soaring fuel costs and a soft Northeast
economy have made the airline unprofitable. The next payment,
about $1.1 million, is due in three weeks.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A Citibank executive said the bank was scheduled to
communicate last night with about 20 banks that purchased
pieces of the shuttle loan and urge them to allow Mr. Trump
to defer interest and principal payments.
   "This isn't about being mad at Donald," said a Citibank
official. "We have to look at this and analyze it in an
unemotional manner."
   Should the participants not agree to go along with a
deferral of interest, Mr. Trump could lose control of the
shuttle, which he bought in 1989 while taking on $380 million
in debt. However, under Mr. Trump's multibank bailout
agreement, a default on the shuttle wouldn't necessarily
trigger a default of the entire agreement, which allows Mr.
Trump to defer interest on almost $1 billion of his $2
billion in bank debt. The accord doesn't cover $1.2 billion
of casino bonds that will most likely be restructured in the
coming months.
   Under the bank deal, Mr. Trump agreed to continue payments
on $245 million in debt issued by Citibank. An additional
$135 million unsecured loan from Citibank and participants
has already been deferred under the deal.
   While Mr. Trump probably will be able to meet the
forthcoming $1.1 million payment, he is not expected to be
able to keep up with the payments due in the next 12 months,
said Stephen Bollenbach, chief financial officer of the Trump
Organization. Those payments are expected to total about $30
million.
   "We don't owe a huge amount right now but we need to
maintain our ability to run the company," Mr. Bollenbach
said. In addition to Messrs. Bollenbach and Trump, Trump
Shuttle President Richard Cozzi attended the meeting with
Citibank officials.
   A Citibank official said last month's shuttle ridership
was off 16% from August 1989. In recent weeks, fuel costs
have risen to 95 cents a gallon from about 50 cents a gallon.
Trump executives are said to believe that matters will not
improve within the next few months.
   Convincing the participants in the bank loan to give Mr.
Trump more time may be difficult. Many of the banks were
reluctant to join August's bank bailout and did so only after
Trump officials assured them that their payments would
continue.
   "The ink isn't even dry yet on the last agreement," said
one individual from a Japanese bank that purchased a piece of
the shuttle loan. As of yesterday, that bank had not been
contacted either by Trump officials or by Citibank officials.
   Mr. Bollenbach said he was sympathetic with the banks'
unhappiness over recent developments. "The situation has
degenerated so quickly that what someone told them a month
ago looks silly by now," he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900920-0088
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900920-0088.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media -- Advertising:
   ABC Rides Radio Waves to Tout
   Three of Its Fall TV Programs
   ----
   By Thomas R. King
</HL>
<DATE>
09/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6
</SO>
<CO>
   CCB GREY SAA F.EUC WNEWS
</CO>
<IN>
ADVERTISING, MARKETING, PUBLIC RELATIONS (ADV)
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
TEXTILES AND APPAREL (TEX)
</IN>
<LP>
   In an effort to add a new twist to the old tactic of radio
promotion, the ABC network plans an aggressive campaign in
five big U.S. markets designed to woo coveted 18-to-34
year-old viewers to three of its fall TV programs.
   The radio campaign, which is just now getting under way,
involves elaborate deals with popular radio personalities who
have agreed to host offbeat, sometimes gimmicky, special
events and award prizes such as a "Twin Peaks" T-shirt, a
"Cop Rock" cap or a "China Beach" cassette tape.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   All of the networks air radio ads and run promotions to
pitch their shows. But ABC says its promotion is different
from other networks' "watch and win" ads, which award prizes
to TV viewers who can answer trivia questions about their
shows. ABC says its promotions, instead, have been designed
to create long-term interest by playing on the shows'
creative appeal.
   "It's an extension of the entertainment," says Mark
Zakarin, vice president of marketing at ABC Entertainment.
"This isn't `We're going to give you something just so you'll
watch it.'"
   The promotions are different in each market. In Chicago,
for example, radio station WKQX will host an event to promote
"Twin Peaks" called "Hide the Body." Chicagoans driving to
work will be challenged to locate a local radio personality
who is wrapped in plastic and hiding somewhere in the city.
The other markets are New York, Los Angeles, Philadelphia and
San Francisco.
   Executives at rival network CBS scoffed at the plan,
saying the Capital Cities/ABC network is just scrambling to
play catch-up because it doesn't have a link with a major
retailer or fast-food chain to boost its fall-season
fortunes. CBS is in the midst of a giant promotion with K
mart; General Electric's NBC has linked with McDonald's.
   "We all do very aggressive local marketing," says George
Schweitzer, senior vice president at CBS. "Radio was very
effective in helping `Uncle Buck' beat `The Fresh Prince of
Bel-Air' {on NBC} this week."
   John D. Miller, executive vice president of marketing at
NBC, said his network, too, has explored the options of
expanded radio promotions. "At this point, the networks are
looking at every possible vehicle to reach a consumer that's
going to watch TV. We're all screaming loud in as many places
as we can."
   Mr. Zakarin insists the ABC promotions are different
because they are so highly targeted and are designed to build
enthusiasm among specific viewer prospects. ABC developed the
program with its ad agency, Grey Advertising, and Local
Marketing Corp. of Cincinnati.
   Further, he says the real value of the program is in the
"stamp of editorial endorsement" that the shows will get from
the radio personalities, who will talk about the shows on the
air. "People spend time every morning on their way to work
listening to these personalities and they have an important
connection with them. It's kind of akin to when Johnny Carson
on `The Tonight Show' says something positive about a movie
he recently saw."
   ABC has been an outspoken critic of the giant
cross-promotions the other networks have coordinated. "Our
research indicated that there was only a negligible increase
in sampling as a result of those cross promotions" last year,
Mr. Zakarin says. "With those promotions, you end up spending
an awful lot of air time not promoting your shows, but
promoting contests."
   New CBS shows attracted lots of viewers early in the fall
of 1989 following the network's first promotion with K mart.
But later, the network had its worst showing ever in the
critical November "sweeps" rating period, suggesting viewers
watched some shows once or twice, but then left in droves.
   For now, Mr. Zakarin is betting the targeted radio
promotions will help to stir up grassroots support for the
shows. TV ads are still the network's best weapon for
promoting shows, he says, "but you have to speak to the
audience very directly at the local level, too."
   ---
   Saatchi Stays Put
                                                                                                       

   Saatchi &amp; Saatchi Co. broke off talks with Canadian
developer Olympia &amp; York about moving its flagship London
agency to Canary Wharf, a huge office development on the
Thames.
   Some analysts believed the cash-strapped communications
giant might reap savings of up to #10 million ($19.1 million)
by relocating the Charlotte Street agency. Olympia &amp; York,
owned by Toronto's Reichmann family, has had trouble
attracting tenants to Canary Wharf.
   Saatchi decided on Friday that any potential savings
wouldn't be enough to offset initial costs and opposition
from staff and clients to an inconvenient move, analysts
reported. A Saatchi spokesman said the company had decided
against a Canary Wharf move until further notice.
   Analysts predicted Saatchi instead might raise nearly $500
million by selling Backer Spielvogel Bates Worldwide, one of
its two international ad groups. Chief Executive Robert
Louis-Dreyfus insists the network isn't for sale -- despite
unsolicited approaches recently from two large French
agencies, Eurocom S.A. and Roux, Seguela, Cayzac &amp; Goudard.
Ad industry executives say that, privately, Mr. Louis-Dreyfus
is shopping for a buyer and the Eurocom discussions may turn
serious.
   The Saatchi spokesman also declined to comment on British
press reports that the company is mulling a debt-for-equity
swap to cancel a European convertible preference issue. The
issue could cost Saatchi as much as #211 million when it
comes due in 1993.
   ---
   Ad Notes. . . .
                                                                                                       

   WATCH ACCOUNT: Tag-Heuer SA, a Swiss watch manufacturer,
awarded its $5 million U.S. ad account to Wells, Rich,
Greene, New York. The account had been handled by Ammirati &amp;
Puris, also of New York. The move consolidates Tag-Heuer's
world-wide advertising: French agency BDDP, which owns a 40%
stake in Wells Rich, continues as the world-wide agency of
record for the watch manufacturer.
                                                                                                       

   JOINT VENTURE: Ketchum International, a unit of Ketchum
Communications, Pittsburgh, formed a joint venture with
Adplus, a Korean advertising agency. Terms weren't disclosed.
The new company, called Adplus Ketchum, will be headed by
Frank Lee, executive vice president of Adplus.
                                                                                                       

   BELATED SAATCHI EXIT: Two top Saatchi &amp; Saatchi executives
dismissed last spring finally completed a settlement with the
company on Friday. The deal, originally expected in late
July, gives Roy Warman and Terry Bannister freedom to operate
their own agency while they remain long-term Saatchi
consultants. But the settlement omits any big cash payments,
knowledgeable observers say.
                                                                                                       

   WHO'S NEWS: Lowe &amp; Partners, New York, named Joan Overlock
executive vice president, account management. She was a
senior vice president at Wells, Rich, Greene.
