<HL>
   Business Brief -- Pennzoil Co.:
   U.S. Court Backs Purchase
   Of 8.8% Stake in Chevron
</HL>
<DATE>
09/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   CHV PZL
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
OIL, INTEGRATED MAJORS (OIL)
PETROLEUM (PET)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   A federal district court threw out Chevron Corp.'s
challenge to the Pennzoil Co. purchase of a stake in the San
Francisco-based oil giant.
   U.S. District Judge Samuel Conti of San Francisco found
that Pennzoil didn't violate antitrust law when it bought
8.8% of Chevron's common stock outstanding for $2.1 billion
in open-market purchases last fall. Chevron had sought to
block the purchase on grounds that Pennzoil misrepresented
its intentions.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Pennzoil said it was "delighted" with the ruling. The
Houston-based company has spent $2.1 billion of the $2.6
billion it won in its highly publicized legal battle with
Texaco Inc. to buy into Chevron. In July, Pennzoil said it
was considering additional purchases of Chevron stock with
the remaining Texaco settlement proceeds.
   Chevron said it would consider an appeal, but must review
the opinion first. "We're disappointed with the outcome,"
said Kenneth T. Derr, Chevron's chairman and chief executive
officer.
   Pennzoil has maintained that it bought the stake for
investment purposes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900920-0047
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900920-0047.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Foreign Exchange:
   Sterling Skids as Bundesbank Chief Airs
   Concerns About Pegging Pound to Mark
   ----
   By Thomas L. Waite
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C11
</SO>
<CO>
   CANDA EUROP FREST JAPAN
</CO>
<IN>
FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
PRECIOUS METALS, STONES, GOLD, SILVER (PCS)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Sterling tumbled after the Bundesbank
president said "big problems" in Britain's economy raise
questions about whether the pound can be pegged tightly to
the mark within the European Monetary System.
   Later, in answer to a question from a Reuters reporter,
Karl Otto Poehl said he didn't pass judgment on whether the
pound is ready to enter the EMS's exchange-rate mechanism.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   But the market reacted strongly because his earlier
remarks seemed to fit a pattern of sniping between Britain
and Germany over European cooperation, said Marc Cohen, a
corporate foreign-exchange trader in New York for Fuji Bank.
   In late New York trading, sterling was quoted at $1.8845,
down from $1.9140 late Tuesday in New York. Against the mark,
the British currency slid to 2.9615 marks late in the day
from 2.9724 marks late Tuesday.
   Meanwhile, the dollar rose against the mark but slid
against the Japanese currency. Late in the New York trading
day, the U.S. currency was at 1.5715 marks, up from 1.5530
marks late Tuesday. It declined to 137.52 yen from 137.85
yen.
   In early trading in Tokyo Thursday, the dollar was quoted
at 137.35 yen, down from 138.05 yen at the close there
Wednesday. Meanwhile, the U.S. currency was trading at about
1.5695 marks, up from Wednesday's Tokyo close of 1.5526
marks.
   Pound selling on the Poehl comments in the early European
afternoon began in the mark cross sector and spread to the
dollar and yen. Similarly, it was a technical floor in the
sterling-mark price that limited the pound's losses
generally.
   The British currency has appreciated about 14% since early
summer on speculation of imminent entry into the
exchange-rate mechanism -- which would give sterling a stable
price range as well as its current advantage of high domestic
interest rates. Such rates make a currency attractive to
international investors.
   But the German central banker's remarks cast a cloud over
sterling. His opinion is considered crucial because Europe's
exchange-rate mechanism is anchored by the mark. Moreover,
the Bundesbank, along with other European central banks,
would be obliged to spend its own money to support the pound
were the British currency to depreciate after joining the
exchange-rate mechanism.
   In a thinly veiled reference to Britain, Mr. Poehl said a
country with "three times the inflation" of Germany can't
expect to peg its currency to the mark for long without
requiring "enormous" intra-European Community transfer
payments. He didn't elaborate.
   A U.K. Treasury spokesman responded: "We have announced
our intention to enter {the exchange-rate mechanism} when the
time is right, and our position remains unchanged."
   Sterling's decline yesterday was exaggerated by the
dollar's firmness after the first hints of Federal Reserve
concern about the greenback's recent losses.
   Testifying before the Joint Economic Committee of
Congress, Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan said "the weaker dollar
adds upward pressure to U.S. import prices and hence raises
further concern about inflation and instability."
   Erik Lehtis, a New York dealer with France's Credit
Agricole, said "Greenspan's suggestion that there's a
downside to the dollar's decline gave the market ideas that
he won't let the dollar fall any further."
   But currency traders plucked Mr. Greenspan's comment about
the dollar out of a wide-ranging testimony that many
considered contradictory. "People were picking parts {of the
testimony} to trade on," said Jeff Mondschein, managing
director of foreign exchange for Continental Bank in Chicago.
   Fed watchers were uncertain what action, if any, Mr.
Greenspan would take to support the dollar. His concern
seemed to put him at odds with the Treasury, which is thought
to be a dominant partner in joint market interventions. On
Monday, Treasury Undersecretary David Mulford called the
dollar's retreat orderly and credited it with helping to
close the U.S. trade deficit.
   Dealers said Mr. Greenspan's remarks appeared to be aimed
at the dollar's mark price, which remains near a record low
of 1.5385 marks, set Aug. 27, and not its yen price, still
about 17 yen above its low of 120.95 yen, set Nov. 24, 1988.
   The dollar ended European dealings moderately stronger,
helped largely by covering of short positions after Mr.
Greenspan's comments. But London dealers said market
participants are still holding substantial short, or
oversold, dollar positions. That should continue to support
the U.S. currency.
   The dollar finished mixed in Tokyo after a session of
active trading, while the yen declined. The dollar was last
quoted Wednesday in Tokyo at 138.05 yen, above 137.68 yen
late Tuesday.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold for current
delivery settled at $386 an ounce, down $1.60. Estimated
volume was a moderate 3.1 million ounces.
   In early trading in Hong Kong Thursday, gold was quoted at
$385.55 an ounce.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900920-0046
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900920-0046.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Pentagon Plans
   On Permanent
   Presence in Gulf
   ---
   Officials Quietly Seek Force
   Of Almost 10,000, Bases,
   After Crisis Is Resolved
   ----
   By Andy Pasztor
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   MDEST
</CO>
<GV>
DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)
STATE DEPARTMENT (STD)
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
</GV>
<LP>
   DHAHRAN, Saudi Arabia -- Senior U.S. military officers are
pushing to keep a permanent force of nearly 10,000 American
troops in this country and to secure air bases throughout the
Persian Gulf after the current crisis is resolved.
   According to senior military officers here and in
Washington, the Army and Air Force are quietly drafting
long-term plans to stay in the gulf in force. The plans also
call for leaving behind huge stockpiles of U.S. weapons and
equipment for use in any future emergency.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   But in Washington, top civilian officials at the Pentagon
and elsewhere in the Bush administration strongly denied that
there is a U.S. policy to establish a permanent presence
here. Their comments could presage an internal battle over
what to do when the crisis with Iraq ends, pitting the
uniformed military against civilian leaders.
   Asked about the military planning, chief Pentagon
spokesman Pete Williams said flatly: "We have no intention of
doing that." He added, "We've been too busy dealing with the
crisis at hand. No one has been authorized to do any planning
beyond that."
   Mr. Williams said, "Maybe somebody is spinning out some
eventuality. The Pentagon is a big place, and there are lots
of people in the Pentagon who think they have the big
picture. But as far as I know, there is no such plan." State
Department officials, who have repeatedly denied any interest
in a permanent ground presence here, expressed similar
surprise and dismay at the officers' planning.
   Military officers said the plans haven't been approved by
Defense Secretary Dick Cheney, Chairman Colin Powell of the
Joint Chiefs of Staff, or President Bush. But the planning is
being handled at a high level in the Army, including some
officers on the staff of Army Chief of Staff Gen. Carl Vuono.
And Saudi officials said the issue has been discussed
informally with them.
   The Saudis, for their part, appear lukewarm about the
idea. "We have strongly resisted such a step over the years,"
noted one Saudi official familiar with the latest
discussions. "But that's clearly what the {U.S.} Army wants,
and the opposition may be reduced this time."
   Even informal talk about permanent bases -- a goal the
U.S. has sought for years -- could make Arab allies nervous
and strain the coalition against Iraq.
   Nevertheless, the Army's leadership is quietly drafting
plans to maintain at least a heavy mechanized brigade and
support forces here indefinitely, according to the officers.
That would total 7,000 or 8,000 troops, and the Army wants to
leave enough hardware on the ground here to support five or
six times that many troops in case of another crisis.
   The Air Force, meanwhile, hopes to win permanent bases in
Oman, the United Arab Emirates and Kuwait, according to
military planners. And the Marines are beating the drums to
have more of their tanks and other weapons placed on
permanent floating storage sites in the Middle East.
   The Pentagon's efforts contradict public signals by the
Bush administration. Just last Friday, on a visit to Syria,
Secretary of State Baker declared that "We have no intention
or desire to establish a permanent military ground presence
in this region." After initially hinting that a new "regional
security structure" for the Middle East might involve U.S.
troops, Mr. Baker repeatedly has said any U.S. contribution
would be likely to be limited to the naval forces the U.S.
has maintained in and near the gulf for 40 years.
   Separately, administration officials said they believe
that 15 pro-Iranian terrorists, whose fate has been linked to
that of the U.S. hostages in Lebanon, are in Iran or on their
way there. The terrorists, who were being held by Kuwait for
a series of 1983 bombings, include the brother-in-law of a
kidnapper who holds two U.S. hostages in Lebanon and has
demanded that the group be freed in exchange for the U.S.
hostages.
   With the prisoners in Iranian hands, another release of
U.S. hostages might be possible. But administration officials
aren't expecting anything soon.
   Meanwhile, Iraq announced that it is confiscating assets
of nations that are participating in economic sanctions
against Iraq. The order applies to assets of U.S. companies
doing business in Iraq. The U.S. government didn't have any
immediate estimate of the value of U.S. assets involved. The
total probably isn't great, though.
   "It is not clear from the Iraqi statement in what form or
against whom the action will be taken," said State Department
spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler. "In any case, actions like
this can only make it more difficult for Iraq to return to
the international community of nations and to restore
economic relations which are crucial for Iraq's long-term
development."
   Meanwhile, the State Department said all Americans who
wish to leave Iraq and Kuwait, and who have been permitted to
do so by Iraqi authorities, will be flown out by Saturday.
Some Americans have chosen to stay, and many others -- mainly
men -- are being refused permission to go.
</TEXT>
