<HL>
   Giving a Hand:
   Ernst &amp; Young Gives Olympic Effort
   To Put U.S. Athletes on Right Track
   ----
   By John A. Conway
</HL>
<DATE>
09/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2
</SO>
<LP>
   {From time to time in this column, The Wall Street Journal
will report on efforts by people in business to help others
in need.}
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   POSITION WANTED: Super-healthy college graduate,
powerfully motivated, highly competitive, totally
inexperienced, seeks executive post. Will require minimum
three months' time off for athletic pursuits.
                                                                                                       

   A WANT AD LIKE THAT SOUNDS like an adolescent pipe dream
but it fits any American hoping to compete in the Olympic
Games. The average age of a U.S. team member is now a mature
25 years and training expenses for a shot at the gold can hit
$40,000 a year. Unlike state-supported foreign competitors,
most U.S. athletes foot their own bills. Now Ernst &amp; Young, a
$2 billion auditing and consulting firm, is putting them in
the starting blocks.
   In 1977, the U.S. Olympic Committee set up its Olympic Job
Opportunity Program and by 1984 had put 276 athletes on
career paths. That year, Ernst &amp; Young, which handled scoring
for the Los Angeles Games, volunteered to help. By 1988, the
firm had placed 162 more athletes. Since September 1989, 164
Olympic strivers have been placed, a year that topped any
previous non-Olympic year. By the time the 1992 Summer
Olympics start in Barcelona, Spain, Ernst &amp; Young hopes to
have 400 Olympians at work.
   James Taylor, Ernst &amp; Young's marketing director, runs the
placement program. The Olympians, he points out, are
incredibly efficient at sports but naive outside the arena.
To help place the 176 athletes now in the program, he is
using 500 volunteers from the firm's 25,000 employees.
"Mentors" in 28 offices go one-on-one with the athletes,
review their resumes, and use the firm's good offices to
match them with employers.
   Ed Brodie, a senior manager in the New York executive
search operation, has three Olympians on his string, a 1988
gold-winning sprinter and two top fencers. One, runner Andrew
Valman, is working at Eastman Kodak as a sales
representative. Mr. Brodie estimates that he puts in 10 to 20
hours a week on his volunteer job, an important consideration
in a profession that starts the meter when the phone rings.
   In Los Angeles, Elizabeth Hammond spends 25% of her time
on her nine charges. Her job, she says, is to "find a label"
for a candidate's skills. "The athletes," she says, "must
analyze themselves, something they are good at."
   The Olympians offer more than glamour and muscles, Mr.
Taylor points out. "Athletes learn from their failures," he
says, a valuable trait in any employee. The grueling
training, he adds, takes dedication, organization and staying
power, qualities most employers long for.
   Olympic rower Kevin Still, a bronze medalist in the 1988
Seoul Games, is on the fast track at New York insurance
broker Johnson &amp; Higgins in New York. "These guys are our
future," says J&amp;H director Norman Barham. Kayaker Mike
Herbert of Arkansas got to the 1988 Olympics because of his
job at J.C. Penney; the company has hired 27 other athletes
through the OJOP program. "I couldn't have done it without
their help," Mr. Herbert says. Anheuser-Busch has taken on 50
Olympians over the years and vice president Jack McDonald
says "everyone's a winner" in the program.
   What does Ernst &amp; Young get out of all this? The tangibles
are publicity, special invitations to U.S. Olympic Committee
events and the right to put a special torch-and-Olympic-ring
symbol on the company's stationery. But the real plus is the
satisfaction of knowing that the firm is finding post-Olympic
careers for the best amateur athletes in the U.S.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900920-0038
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900920-0038.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Real Estate:
   Reichmanns Act
   To Sell Chunk
   Of Real Estate
   ----
   By Neil Barsky and Mitchell Pacelle
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
REAL ESTATE INVESTMENTS (REA)
</IN>
<LP>
   The Reichmann family, which owns Olympia &amp; York
Developments Ltd., is seeking to sell almost a 20%
partnership interest in its massive U.S. real estate
portfolio.
   John Zuccotti, Olympia &amp; York USA president, declined to
estimate the value of the stake, but real-estate
professionals said the interest could sell for between $200
million and $800 million. Mr. Zuccotti denied speculation
that the company, as with many real estate concerns, has a
cash-flow problem. He added that the planned transaction had
been in the works for many months.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Zuccotti said the move is intended to put in the hands
of a single institutional investor minority holdings in
properties controlled by a variety of Reichmann family
members. The corporate entity will be unaffected by the sale,
said O&amp;Y officials.
   The properties, which include commercial projects in New
York City, Boston, San Francisco and other major U.S. cities,
are being shopped to a variety of institutional investors,
although the ultimate buyer is expected to be foreign.
   Lazard Freres &amp; Co. has been retained by the Reichmanns to
handle the sale.
   Observers of O&amp;Y's activities are keenly interested in the
sale because they think it may signal that the Reichmanns are
protecting themselves against a more severe downturn in the
real-estate market.
   One individual who has spoken to family leader Paul
Reichmann said that while Mr. Reichmann does not believe in
the "gloom and doom scenario, it's enough of a possibility
that he's hedging his bets."
   In the past, the Reichmanns have made fortunes by
correctly anticipating swings in the real estate and credit
markets. In perhaps its most prescient move, the company
purchased the Uris family's New York City real-estate
portfolio in 1977 for $320 million. Those properties were
said to have increased tenfold in value during the 1980s.
   O&amp;Y also developed the successful World Financial Center
in the 1980s. Its tenants include the world headquarters of
American Express Co., Merrill Lynch &amp; Co., and Dow Jones &amp;
Co., publisher of this newspaper.
   Lately, however, the O&amp;Y's fortunes have taken a slight
turn for the worse, in part because of its heavy investment
in the troubled Campeau Corp.
   Olympia &amp; York also has spent more than $1 billion
building the world's largest real-estate development in the
London docklands. That project, called Canary Wharf, is 50%
leased, but its success is far from certain. The company is
in the midst of securing long-term bank financing from
British and Japanese institutions.
   Some of the company's older, Wall Street-area buildings,
such as one once occupied by Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., sit
largely empty.
   Nonetheless, during the past two decades, O&amp;Y has
diversified into a number of industries that provide hedges
against major drops in the real-estate market. It owns a
controlling interest in newsprint producer Abitibi-Price Inc.
and Consumers' Gas Co. It also owns a 73% interest in Gulf
Canada Resources Ltd., which has benefited from the recent
rise in oil prices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
