<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
09/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   THE ECONOMY is moving closer to a recession as a result of
the jump in oil prices, Fed Chairman Greenspan told Congress.
He said the central bank's ability to resist a recession by
lowering interest rates has been frustrated by inflationary
pres sures. However, he didn't rule out a long-anticipated
move to lower rates.
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   A Fed survey shows that the Mideast crisis already is
raising manufacturers' costs, damping consumer buying and
causing widespread uncertainty in the business community.
   ---
   Northwest Airlines received a $500 million cash infusion
from Airbus Industrie and General Electric. The European
consortium arranged the low-interest loan after Northwest
agreed to buy 75 more Airbus planes and take options on 30
others. A GE team will supply the engines for the aircraft.
   ---
   Pan Am plans to slash 2,500 jobs, eliminate some
trans-Atlantic service and shift to smaller planes to combat
higher fuel costs and light traffic.
   ---
   Northrop's chairman retired just as an International
Chamber of Commerce ruling surfaced saying that $6.2 million
in payments by the firm to South Korea were meant to induce
Seoul to buy Northrop fighter planes.
   ---
   The Reichmann family is trying to sell a nearly 20%
partnership interest in its U.S. real estate portfolio.
Industry officials said the stake could fetch as much as $800
million.
   ---
   The FCC approved broad changes in the way it regulates
fees long-distance carriers pay for access to local phone
networks. It projected billions of dollars in savings for
consumers, but some user groups were skeptical.
   ---
   American General said it may settle for selling only its
home-service life insurance business, claiming it's having
trouble finding a buyer for the entire financial-services
concern.
   ---
   The S&amp;L bailout agency told a House panel that it will
need about $122 billion in funding for the fiscal year
starting Oct. 1, more than double what was anticipated a year
ago.
   ---
   Donald Trump wants to restructure $245 million in debt
payments still due on loans made for the Trump Shuttle. Mr.
Trump cited soaring fuel costs and a soft Northeast economy.
   ---
   Small investors seeking punitive damages in arbitration
disputes with brokers suffered a setback when a judge ruled
punitive damages can't always be awarded in such cases.
   ---
   First Executive's claims that unreleased reports prove its
long-term financial viability appear to fall far short of
that assertion.
   ---
   The budget standoff isn't giving a political advantage to
the Republicans or the Democrats, a Wall Street Journal/NBC
News poll found.
   ---
   The life insurance industry is likely to see its federal
tax bill jump by $2 billion a year, partly because stock and
mutual insurance companies haven't resolved a tax squabble.
   ---
   Time Warner will consolidate its publishing operations
into a new unit that will include its magazine business and
book publishing operation.
   ---
   The GAO is concerned bank regulators are making some of
the same mistakes that led to the S&amp;L crisis.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 147,530,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2557.43, off 13.86; transportation 888.31, off 13.13;
utilities 201.52, up 1.00.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Brothers Treasury index 3345.45, up
16.30.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 131.66, off 0.62;
spot index 128.90, off 0.53.
   Dollar: 137.52 yen, off 0.33; 1.5715 marks, up 0.0185.
