<HL>
   Technology:
   New Compound Developed
   For Superconductivity
</HL>
<DATE>
09/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   HIT
</CO>
<IN>
ELECTRICAL COMPONENTS AND EQUIPMENT (ELQ)
</IN>
<LP>
   BOSTON -- Hitachi Ltd. said its researchers developed a
compound that shows signs of superconductivity at a somewhat
higher temperature than previously reported for the
phenomenon.
   The new compound, unlike most "high-temperature"
superconductors developed during the past few years, doesn't
contain copper -- an aspect of the material that intrigues
superconductivity experts.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   They hope the new compound will provide clues about how to
make superconductors that work at yet higher and more cheaply
attained temperatures.
   Superconductors, which conduct electricity without
resistance when cooled, promise new electrical technologies,
such as faster computers and cheaper power generation.
   The Japanese concern said its new material contains the
elements thallium, strontium, vanadium and oxygen; the
company also reported fabricating a closely related
superconductor in which part of the strontium is replaced
with the element cerium.
   A sample of Hitachi's compound showed a sharp drop in
electrical resistance -- indicating superconductivity --
between 130 Kelvins and 160 Kelvins, or minus 225 degrees
Fahrenheit to minus 171 degrees Fahrenheit, Hitachi said.
Currently, the highest known temperature for
superconductivity is about 125 Kelvins, or minus 234 degrees
Fahrenheit.
   The finding hasn't yet been confirmed, and some scientists
said they were skeptical about it. During the past few years,
several research teams have reported similar
superconductivity temperature advances that apparently were
spurious.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900920-0022
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900920-0022.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Nuclear Plants Don't Boost
   Cancer Deaths, Study Says
</HL>
<DATE>
09/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<IN>
NUCLEAR POWER, FUEL (NUK)
ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)
AEROSPACE (ARO)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
HEALTH AND HUMAN SERVICES (HHS)
ENERGY DEPARTMENT (ERG)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The National Cancer Institute found that
people who live near nuclear facilities don't face a greater
risk of death from cancer than those who live elsewhere.
   The NCI compared mortality data in 107 counties
surrounding all 62 U.S. nuclear facilities -- 52 commercial
power plants, nine Department of Energy research and weapons
plants, and one commercial fuel-reprocessing plant -- in
operation before 1982 with data from demographically similar
counties that weren't close to nuclear facilities.
Researchers found "no evidence to suggest that the occurrence
of leukemia or any other form of cancer was generally higher
in the study counties than the control counties."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Both proponents and opponents of nuclear power agree that
the NCI survey is the nation's most comprehensive assessment
of the relationship between proximity to nuclear facilities
and cancer mortality.
   But Sen. Edward Kennedy (D., Mass.), who requested the
study, said the study "isn't a clean bill of health for the
nuclear industry" because it didn't go far enough. In
contrast, the U.S. Council for Energy Awareness, a nuclear
trade group, said the study "should put the public at ease
that living near a nuclear plant isn't harmful to their
health."
   No matter how reassuring its findings, the study isn't
likely to improve the prospects for the construction of new
nuclear plants. Because of concerns about cost, nuclear waste
disposal, safety and regulatory delay, there hasn't been an
order for a new nuclear plant in the U.S. since 1978.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900920-0021
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900920-0021.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Big Western Investment
   In Eastern Europe Planned
</HL>
<DATE>
09/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A11
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP JAPAN
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Large Western companies are gearing up to
invest billions of dollars in Eastern Europe over the next
five years, a new survey indicates.
   More than 30% of the corporations polled plan to spend a
total of $3.2 billion in Eastern Europe in the next five
years, according to accounting firm DRT International.
Another 33% plan investments but didn't say how much. DRT
surveyed 128 companies world-wide with assets or sales of
more than $1 billion.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Most companies planning to invest in Eastern Europe intend
to do so through joint ventures with existing Eastern
European enterprises. Export-import opportunities, which are
particularly popular among Japanese companies, came in
second.
   In the survey, 23 European companies said they expect to
invest $1.7 billion; 13 U.S. companies, $332 million; and 12
Japanese companies, $1.1 billion.
   Nearly all of the Western Europe respondents do business
in Eastern Europe or plan to do so in the next five years;
more than half of the North American and 63% of Japanese
companies said they expect to have a stake in Eastern Europe
in the future.
