<HL>
   Economy:
   August Housing Starts Fell
   For Seventh Month in a Row
</HL>
<DATE>
09/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<IN>
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
ECONOMIC AND MONETARY INDICATORS (EMI)
HOME CONSTRUCTION (HOM)
</IN>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Housing starts fell for the seventh
consecutive month in August for their longest decline in
eight years.
   Builders started work on new homes at an annual rate of
1,127,000 last month, the Commerce Department said, down 1.7%
from July's 1,147,000. August starts were running 15% below a
year earlier. They haven't fallen for seven months in a row
since the last recession in 1981-82.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   These are the first housing-start figures to appear since
the Iraqi invasion of Kuwait and might reflect shaky
confidence in the wake of the crisis. "Frankly, I think the
housing industry probably would have begun to rebound by
August if not for the Persian Gulf crisis," said Mark
Obrinsky, a senior economist at the Federal National Mortgage
Association.
   Starts on single-family homes fell 3.2% last month to an
annual rate of 840,000 after declining 2.4% in July to
868,000. Starts on apartments and other multifamily dwellings
rose 2.9% in August to an annual rate of 287,000 units after
plunging 7% in July to 279,000.
   Despite these figures, however, David Seider, chief
economist for the National Association of Home Builders, said
the market for multifamily dwellings is in a "bona fide
recession condition," with the falloff in single-family
housing starts less dire.
   All the numbers were adjusted for seasonal fluctuations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900920-0018
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900920-0018.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Business Brief -- Public Service Co. of Colorado:
   Borrowing Is Seen to Pay
   For Converting Idled Plant
</HL>
<DATE>
09/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   PSR
</CO>
<IN>
ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)
NUCLEAR POWER, FUEL (NUK)
</IN>
<LP>
   Public Service Co. of Colorado, Denver, said it expects to
borrow, either through a private placement or public
offering, about $200 million to help pay costs associated
with converting its idled nuclear electric generating plant
to natural gas power.
   The utility said it expects to use about $125 million of
the borrowing to pay for removing the remains of radioactive
fuel from the St. Vrain plant north of Denver. PS Colorado
stopped generating electricity at the plant, the nation's
only gas-cooled, high-temperature reactor, in August 1989
after 10 years because of operational problems and excessive
costs. The company said it may have to spend $47 million of
the borrowed funds to build a temporary storage facility for
spent fuel from the plant.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   PS Colorado said state regulators cleared a private
placement, though plans are still preliminary. It hasn't
filed documents with the Securities and Exchange Commission
on a possible public bond offering. It said it doesn't expect
now to use any of the funds to finance the plant's $85
million dismantling and conversion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
